2pt">Ninety two percent of Cornwall’s working population live and work within its region and our economic functionality was a key reason why the Cornwall and Isles of Scilly Local Enterprise Partnership was set up. Having only two local authorities covered by </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">one Local </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Enterprise Partnership has given</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> strength and clarity of purpose. With a recognised brand and clear devolution aspirations, Cornwall, together with the Isles of Scilly if they wish, should have the opportunity to aspire to greater autonomy. This </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">is not just an issue for cities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:14.98pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In November 2011 Cornwall submitted a bid to the Department for Communities and Local Government to become a Whole Place Community Budget Pilot. In our bid we clearly articulated our ambition to gain more control over our own affairs, including the ability</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> to reduce our reliance on Government funding through greater financial freedoms and by establishing innovative funding mechanisms. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">strength </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">of Cornwall </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">is our simple geography which provides co-terminosity with our key public sector partners, and with t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">he Isles of Scilly through our strategic partnerships.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How public services, including employment, skills and welfare, should be organised to complement devolution</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.52pt; padding-left:14.98pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Cornwall Council has been innovative in developing alternative service delivery models to p</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">rovide continuity and excellence through the current challenging financial climate. This includes establishing several new arms-length delivery bodies and a new strategic partnership with a private sector partner. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.52pt; padding-left:14.98pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">We believe that the Government should ful</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ly support local areas to remodel services according to local need, and to find innovative solutions, and that the Government should be flexible and pragmatic regarding these new bodies and their ability to operate commercially. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.52pt; padding-left:14.98pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">With devolved powers we</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> envisage a far more integrated public service landscape which can deliver efficiencies through horizontal integration with local partners, as well as vertical integration with government agencies. We already work closely with partners such as the Departme</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">nt of Work and Pensions, the Skills Funding Agency, Highways Agency and Environment Agency but we believe there is more scope to connect functions and integrate services locally.    </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.52pt; padding-left:14.98pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Cornwall has particular challenges regarding employment and skills. We ha</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ve a dispersed population and an economy based predominantly on very small to medium size businesses. It is crucial that we have the ability to tailor support for our local circumstances and that we have </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the flexibility to use funding appropriately, for ex</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ample around NEETs, skills, training and support for the unemployed. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:14.98pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> relatively</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> low GVA has resulted in Cornwall qualifying for significant</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">European funding programmes. Our experience over many years has shown that these programmes need to be</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> as </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">flexibl</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> as possible, both in terms of policy and delivery mechanisms, in order to ensure that bespoke and efficient projects and programmes are delivered for the benefit of local businesses and communities. W</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">e continue to</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> work with the Cornwall and Isles of Scil</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ly Local Enterprise Partnership to argue for maximum flexibility </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> ensure the greatest</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> benefit</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> possible. In the next programme period (2014-2020) we would like to package all EU funding streams within an Integrated Territorial Investment (ITI) mechanism, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">or through being an Intermediary Body, which would allow a more strategic approach for Cornwall and the Isles of Scilly.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How ‘devolved’ areas would be governed, including the role of business in decision making</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.52pt; padding-left:14.98pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Devolution of greater financial responsibility would require a different form of governance. Cornwall Council would continue to provide the legitimate democratic accountability back to the electorate. A fully accountable and transparent governance structur</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">e incorporating the Council, the Local Enterprise Partnership, Local Nature Partnership and the Health and Wellbeing Board could service the requirements of local people and provide direct accountability back to Government. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:14.98pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The strategic partnerships enco</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">mpass all of the key public sector partners. The business community is strongly represented through the Local Enterprise Partnership, and the voluntary and community sector are represented across all of the major partnership structures. We believe that we </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">already have the key components to enable us to establish a robust governance structure to take on additional powers and administer a greater proportion of public funding locally. </span></li></ul><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How ‘devolved’ areas would be held to account</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:14.98pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">There is a growing imperative to reconnect local people with public services by developing a better understanding and greater transparency between the services people receive and the way in which these are financed. This is particularly the case with dimin</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ishing public sector budgets and associated cuts in services. In a devolved environment, the relationship with local tax payers is crucial to provide legitimacy to local funding and commissioning decisions. Our new governance structure would ensure account</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ability to local tax payers as well as satisfying the Government’s requirements for value for money, prudent investment and financial probity.   </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Strength of evidence that devolution would lead to economic growth, local improvement and better local govern</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ance, including examples of what areas could do with their new powers such as use them to invest in infrastructure and local services.</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:14.98pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Whilst the repatriation of a proportion of business rates is a welcome move it does not necessarily create as strong an </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">incentive for economic growth in Cornwa</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ll as in other areas, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">due to the</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">predominance</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> of micro businesses. Our preferred formula to incentivise growth would encompass a range of tax headings and other payments. We have conducted some work on an ‘invest to g</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">row’ methodology which captures the value to the economy through targeted investment in the creation of employment or through major infrastructure projects. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:14.98pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Where new jobs are created, or earnings are increased through investment in training, we have mod</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">elled the resultant value to the Cornish economy and tested how a payment-by-results mechanism might operate, funded from the increased tax take (across a range of tax headings) and from reductions in the benefits bill. We believe that by negotiating this </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">type of ‘deal’ with Government it would provide a clear incentive for growth which better suits our economy. The funding raised would be recycled into new investment areas, sustaining growth through the smarter use of funding that is already in the system.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:14.98pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In our Growth Deal we have set out a range of ‘Asks’ of Government to enable us to gain more control over investment in infrastructure. We would reiterate the need for these freedoms in order for our Local Enterprise Partnership to fulfil the remit to d</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">rive growth.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The impact on areas not included in any new devolution arrangements, including those on city borders and those affected by resulting changes to national financial equalisation and distributive arrangements</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:14.98pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Cornwall has developed a closer w</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">orking relationship with Plymouth through the City Deal process. This is specifically focused on opportunities around the maritime economy and the links between maritime and education at Plymouth University, Falmouth University and major development opport</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">unity in Hayle and Falmouth. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:14.98pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Cornwall’s self-contained economy makes it the ideal test-bed for new devolutionary models as the impact on neighbouring areas would be limited. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What taxes might be devolved – for example council tax, stamp duty and busines</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s rates.</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:14.98pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Although we have conducted some research in this area we have been unable to access the level of information that we need to create a comprehensive picture of income and expenditure for Cornwall. We would request that the Government works to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ensure that accurate data is available at the local level, particularly regarding tax take</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:14.98pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Greater transparency will enable us to better understand the financial flows across our population and will help us to evidence the case for which taxes it may be </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">appropriate to devolve.  In particular we would wish </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">see closer working and easier data sharing with HMRC and DWP at a local level to map the totality of public finances for Cornwall.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>